:"Second cousins — both great-grandsons of Noadiah Russell. Russell co-founded Skull and Bones in 1832, the same year Samuel's Russell & Company reached its peak opium operation in Canton.","link_text":"William Huntington Russell"}],"gender":"male","notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_%26_Company"},"number_of_marriages":2,"bio":{"display_name":"Samuel Wadsworth Russell","first_name":"Samuel","last_name":"Russell","middle_name":"Wadsworth","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST009","institution_blurb":"His 1828 Greek Revival house (LM016, 350 High Street) is now Wesleyan's Department of Philosophy."},{"institution_id":"INST022"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"business","header":"Largest American opium trader in 1830s China","body":"Arrived Canton 1819; founded Samuel Russell & Co.; from 1824 restructured as Russell & Company. By early 1831 had smuggled 3,500 chests of Indian opium into China — approximately twenty percent of the country's total annual opium imports that year. Russell & Company was the largest American opium trading house in China."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"Skull and Bones founded by his Russell cousin","body":"His second cousin William Huntington Russell co-founded Skull and Bones at Yale in 1832 with Alphonso Taft — both Hooker descendants themselves. The Russell family fortune that helped support the society's early decades had been substantially built on his own Russell & Company opium trading at Canton, China."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Business partner was FDR's maternal grandfather","body":"Among the partners at Russell & Company was Warren Delano Jr. — the maternal grandfather of President Franklin Delano Roosevelt. The Russell-Delano connection ran through the China opium trade two generations before Delano's grandson reached the White House."},{"number":4,"category":"architecture","header":"Greek Revival mansion 1828 by Ithiel Town","body":"On returning from Canton 1831 he commissioned a major Greek Revival mansion at Middletown CT, designed 1826-1828 by Ithiel Town — the same architect Daniel Wadsworth used for the Wadsworth Atheneum. The Middletown mansion remains a landmark of the Greek Revival movement in American domestic architecture."},{"number":5,"category":"marriage","header":"Lost his first wife at twenty-three, 1819","body":"Married Mary Cotton Osborn on 6 October 1815 in New York; she died in 1819 leaving him with two sons. Six years later in October 1825 he married her sister Frances Ann Osborn — the family stabilization pattern echoed in many Dwight cousins of his generation."}],"slug":"samuel-russell-1789"},"HD1372":{"id":"HD1372","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00850","mother_id":"X00438"},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1791},"death":{"year":1825},"gender":"female","marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X01646","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":1}],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Lucy Warner Russell Bowers","first_name":"Lucy","last_name":"Bowers","maiden_name":"Russell","middle_name":"Warner","married_names":["Bowers"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"lucy-bowers-1791"},"HD1373":{"id":"HD1373","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00850","mother_id":"X00438"},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1794},"death":{"year":1819},"gender":"female","marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X01647","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":1},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"H01844","date_year":1847,"date_month":6,"date_day":1,"end_type":"death","end_year":1866,"children_ids":["H03329","H03330","H03331"]}],"number_of_marriages":2,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Julia Russell Johnson","first_name":"Julia","last_name":"Johnson","maiden_name":"Russell","married_names":["Johnson"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"julia-johnson-1794"},"HD1374":{"id":"HD1374","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00850","mother_id":"X00438"},"tags":["china_trade","mayor","merchant"],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1797},"death":{"year":1874},"political_offices":[{"title":"Mayor","jurisdiction":"Middletown CT","dates":"1859-1861"},{"title":"State Representative","jurisdiction":"Connecticut","dates":"multiple terms"},{"title":"President","jurisdiction":"Charles River Railroad MA","dates":"unknown"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00444","children_ids":["HD1384","HD1385"],"marriage_number":1}],"gender":"male","notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"China trader; Mayor of Middletown 1859-1861","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Augustus_Russell_House"},"number_of_marriages":1,"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Edward Augustus Russell","first_name":"Edward","last_name":"Russell","middle_name":"Augustus","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST009","institution_blurb":"His 1841-1842 Greek Revival house (LM017, 318 High Street) is now Wesleyan property used for lectures, concerts, and events."},{"institution_id":"INST022"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Russell & Company trader in China, 1825-1838","body":"Edward Augustus Russell joined his elder brother Samuel in China in 1825, working for Russell & Company — the dominant American firm in the Canton trade. He stayed thirteen years, returning to Middletown in 1838. The fortune accumulated in the China trade financed his return to civic life in Connecticut."},{"number":2,"category":"achievement","header":"Built Greek Revival on Noadiah Russell's homelot","body":"In 1841-1842 Russell built a Greek Revival mansion at 318 High Street, Middletown — the last Greek Revival house on what had become the city's most prestigious street. The lot was the original Noadiah Russell homelot, dating to the seventeenth century. Rev. Noadiah Russell had been a founding trustee of Yale in 1701 and was Edward Augustus Russell's great-great-grandfather."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Mayor of Middletown, 1859-1861","body":"Russell served as Mayor of Middletown from 1859 to 1861, as a Connecticut State Representative, and as a national convention delegate. He held railroad directorships including the presidency of the Charles River Railroad in Massachusetts. Both of his sons predeceased him."}],"landmarks_associated":["LM017"],"slug":"edward-russell-1797"},"H00851":{"id":"H00851","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00359","mother_id":"X00437"},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","entry":"851"},{"short":"Barbour Collection, Middletown CT"}],"birth":{"year":1767,"month":10,"day":1,"city":"Middletown","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1838,"month":9,"day":1,"state":"Connecticut","country":"United States","age":70},"gender":"male","marriages":[],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Captain William Russell","first_name":"William","last_name":"Russell","title":"Captain","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Fourteen children across his two marriages","body":"Captain William Russell had fourteen documented children across two marriages — four with his first wife Patience Ranney (1791-1796), and ten more with his unnamed second wife (1799-1819). The first marriage ended in widowhood when Patience died September 22, 1796 at age twenty-five; he remarried within a few years. The compressed reproductive arc across nearly thirty years of his prime adult life produced one of the larger Middletown CT Russell families of the early Republic."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Named daughter Harriet Wadsworth, preserving family line","body":"William named his eldest daughter Harriet Wadsworth Russell — explicitly preserving his Wadsworth-family heritage in her name. The same Wadsworth-naming pattern appeared in the parallel Terry family, where Alfred Terry Sr. named his children Harriet Wadsworth Terry and Jeremiah Wadsworth Terry. Both Connecticut families consciously honored the Wadsworth-Russell ancestral lineage through deliberate naming choices."},{"number":3,"category":"death","header":"First wife Patience Ranney died age twenty-five","body":"William's first wife Patience Ranney died September 22, 1796 in Middletown Connecticut at age twenty-five — six years after their marriage and with four young children. She is buried at Mortimer Cemetery. The early-widowing pattern was typical of late-eighteenth-century Connecticut childbearing-age mortality."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Born Middletown CT 1767, died 1838 age seventy","body":"Captain William Russell was born October 1, 1767 in Middletown Connecticut, son of Captain Samuel Russell and Ruth Whitmore. He died September 1, 1838 at age seventy. The Russell family's Middletown roots ran several generations deep in the river-town that had been founded in the mid-seventeenth century."}],"slug":"william-russell-1767"},"H00852":{"id":"H00852","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00359","mother_id":"X00437"},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","entry":"852"},{"short":"Barbour Collection, Middletown CT"}],"birth":{"year":1776,"month":2,"day":6,"city":"Middletown","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1800,"month":10,"day":16},"gender":"female","marriages":[],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Esther Russell","first_name":"Esther","maiden_name":"Russell","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"esther-russell-1776"},"H00